<<set $hid to 1>>"Follow me," Gretel mouthed, pointing to the side of the cabin. Hansel nodded. The two of them, softly, on tiptoes, danced around the right of the garden bed and made their way to the west wall.\n\nGetting up close, the two children could smell something warm. The scent of cooking bread wafted past their noses. It was coming from a window, embedded into the stone. They peeked inside. \n\nLeather lounges donned around a moderate stone fireplace, with a blooming fire roaring in it pits. The fire cast shadows across a jade rug. \n\nFurther to the left, a small kitchenette boasted a variety of objects to excite two (hungry) children- a basket of mixed berries rested upon a wooden table, vases of rainbow coloured flowers sat next to the hung pots and pans on the far wall, and a bag of flour ... /Heaved?/ \n\nNo, not heaved. "I don't think so," said Gretel. "Father's bag is still here. I bet that they went to gather firewood, too."\n\n"So should we stay here?\n\n"Yes."\n\nMinutes passed. Hansel had found a seat on a nearby log, watching on as his sister attempted to start a fire again. Unsuccessfully.\n\nHe shivered, rubbing his hands together.\n\n"Can we go search now?"\n \nGretel huffed, bothered by the intrusion. "Can you not bother me?"\n\nHansel stared at his feet. "Sorry," he mumbled. "I'm just cold. And... and I think it's not going to work."\n\nExasperated, Gretel shoved the matches into her coat pocket. "Very well."\n\nHansel rose to his feet. "The light would help us search for them very quickly. I don't... I don't think they would have gotten very far."\n\nGretel said nothing, but walked to her brother's [[side|crow appears]]. \n
The two of them out of earshot now, Hansel tugged on his sister's coat.\n\n"I don't like this," he said, with a frown. \n\n"Either do I, but I don't see what we can do about it." Gretel shrugged, and bent over to grab a small log. "Eugh," she said, "it's wet."\n\n"Everything here is wet," Hansel concluded, examining a particular muddy branch. "It's a terrible day to build a fire."\n\nThe two of them scoured their surroundings. After a small scare from Hansel in lodging a disgruntled spider from their hiding place, and a discovery of some pink berries nestled in a bush, the two of them could only muster a miserable bundle of (slightly) muddy branches and dead leaves between them.\n\n"We could head back, drop these off and keep looking," said Gretel, looking at her own collection dismally. \n\nHansel nodded. With a mutually exchanged grimace, the pair began to treck [[back|next]]. \n\n

<em>Nothing</em>.\n\nA small collection of firewood, and their father's backpack, but their parents were nowhere to be seen.\n\n"Father?" Gretel called out. "Mother?"\n\nHer voice echoed through the woods.\n\n"Maybe they went to collect firewood, too," said Hansel, hopefully. \n\nA creeping chill slithered down Gretel's spine. "Maybe." She dropped her bundle over the other wooden branches, and shifted over to reach into her father's backpack. \n\nHansel watched as she drew out a small box of matches. With one fluid flick of the wrist against the box, the match promptly lit up. She bent down, and bought the flame to the dead leaves. A woosh of smoke, and then, nothing.\n\n"I...I was sure that would work."\n\n"Doesn't Ed usually use a special sort of coal-thing to light the fires back home?"\n\nGretel shrugged. "I thought you could start a fire without them."\n\n"You might be able to," offered Hansel, "But I wouldn't know how."\n\nThe two of them stared at the would-be fire. "Mother would know," said Gretel dejectedly. \n\nHansel began digging back into his father's backpack. His hands found a cyclinder object, and he pulled it out to examine <<nobr>><span id="pocketlight"><<click "it.">><<replace "#pocketlight">><<display "pocketlight">><</replace>><</click>></span><<endnobr>>\n\n\n\n
The bright day poured through the tiny holes in the foliage above, sprinkling the forest floor with glowing spotlights. The four of them followed a muddy path through the winding oaks and twisting saplings. The occasional /crunch, crunch/ of stepping on a branch was the only sound exchanged between them. A few minutes in, Gretel dared to break the <<nobr>><span id="excuse"><<click "silence.">><<replace "#excuse">><<display "excuse">><</replace>><</click>></span><<endnobr>>\n

path.\n\n"Here," Father announced, and removed the backpack from his shoulders, lowering it to the ground. "We will rest here for a moment." He turned to face the children. "We will work together to build a small fire as a base." He bent down and unclipped the lock, lifted the flap open, and reached in to retrieve some matches. "Your mother and I will stay here and begin to build the fire. I want the both of you to fetch us some firewood. Nothing wet, nothing too heavy. Do you understand?"\n\nGretel nodded, and took her brother's hand into her own. Silently, the two shuffled past their parents, and began to [[search|search]].

house?\n\nThe first point of interest for Gretel was the garden. Snaking vines up trevasses, thick bushes with blooming flowers, and miniature trees with bulbous fruit barely hanging on. The garden encompassed everything between the cabin and stout wooden gate. \n\nThe first point of interest for Hansel was the roof. A slightly bent chimney puffed out a steady stream of smoke. He watched it trail upwards, with the realisation dawning on him that a lit chimney was a lit fireplace, and a lit fireplace meant that <em>somebody was home</em>.\n\nHansel tugged on his sister's sleeves. "Gretel," he whispered, "I think somebody is inside."\n\nGretel caught on not a second before he spoke. "Look at all their food."\n\nAs if it had been comically timed, Hansel's stomach let out a deep growl. \n\nHis face flushed. Apologetic, he said, "I haven't eaten since this morning."\n\nGretel laughed, and immediately smacked her palm to her mouth, eyes wide. It had been <em>too loud.</em> \n\nHansel glanced at the window, the very same one the crow passed through not a moment earlier. A curtain obscured his view. He then glanced back at the garden.\n\n"I just want those mandarins," he whispered, pointing to a stout tree just left of the path that winded through to the cabin. "We could take one or two, right? And ask Mother and Father to pay it for it?"\n\n<em>Mother and Father</em>. <<nobr>><span id="motherfather"><<click "Mother and Father?">><<replace "#motherfather">><<display "take/leave food">><</replace>><</click>></span><<endnobr>>
children?"\n\nIn the hallway entered a tall, speckled woman with long copper hair and tight skin. The tips of her fingers rolled together in one repetitive motion. In her wake followed a slightly smaller stature man with a long, bushy mane and a short-trim hat that could barely contain his sprawling locks.\n\n"Ah, you both look lovely," said the father, and a small smile emerged from his face. What do you mean by servants? \n\nGretel: [[Our family's pretty rich, so we've never collected firewood before.|rich tale]]\n
"They can't have gotten very far, I suppose. No point in staying with a non-fire-y fire."\n\nA small smile escaped Hansel's mouth, before it shifted back to his typical semi-frown. "Should we take the satchel with us?"\n\nGretel's forehead wrinkled. "Why?"\n\n"Just in case we find Mother and Father."\n\nGretel shook her head. "I don't think that's a good idea. They probably wished to meet back here. It might be hard to find without the satchel here." Gretel bent over to slide the matches underneath the flap. \n\nAs she turned to face her brother, her eyes glanced to the [[animal|crow appears]] behind him.\n\n\n
Behind her brother, perched upon a low-hanging branch, was a snow-white <<nobr>><span id="crow"><<click "crow.">><<replace "#crow">><<display "discovercrow">><</replace>><</click>></span><<endnobr>>
The children stood upright. The two maids asked for them to extend their arms, and in a synchronised motion, slipped their coats through their limbs and straightened the collars.\n\n"Looking sharp, young Hansel," said one maid, respectfully avoiding eye contact. "And as pleasing as ever, Gretel." \n\nThe two children bowed, and both maids shrunk out of the hallway. \n\nA voice called to them. "Are we ready, my <<nobr>><span id="mychildren"><<click "children?">><<replace "#mychildren">><<display "parents">><</replace>><</click>></span><<endnobr>> \n\n\n

It isn't safe right now."\n\nGretel/Hansel scared and confused.\n\n"I can't explain much, but know this. It seems your parents were trying to protect you. And they have done an excellent job, leading you to me both. But don't worry, you'll be safe. Are you both wearing your pendant?"\n\nShocked faces. "How do you know about our pendant?"\n\n"Because you two are the children. Look, I cannot speak about what is to come. But I will keep you both safe, here, trust me." figure takes them by the hands. "I am a stranger to you, I know, but I will [[protect you|bad end lead]]."\n\n

And then they said for us to stay put, and left. And we came here because we saw food."\n\n"I'm so sorry for the both of you. In any case, I'd be happy to provide some food, shelter and sleep, and at the least, help you find your way home. But I think food should we our priority for now. What do you think?"\n\nthe children nod. \n\n[[hours pass...|hours pass]]
The children turned to each one another. \n\n"I don't... I don't think we were... supposed to hear that," the younger one mumbled.\n\n"Either."\n\nThe younger one wrapped his arms around his sister's side. "What festival could they mean?"\n\n"Perhaps the coming harvest celebrations. But I do not know for sure." She lobbed her hand over to ruffle his hair. "We can only wait until the morning."\n\nHe nodded. "Okay."\n\nThe two wandered back to the staircase, and to their bedrooms. A niggle of fear, of nervous antipaction for the [[morrow|begin]].

<style>.passage .header {\n background-image: [img[default forest]];\n}</style>\n\ndad spots them. with a roar, he pushes through and reaches for them. "kids, we have to go now! we are late, we are late!" the figure screams for him to stop, and she lurches after him, but he shoves her to the ground. it.\n\nThe object in question was one of his father's beloved possessions, and what he called a "pocketlight." Hansel had been told his father sought after it from a nearby town. A new invention, it harnessed some sort of energy to beacon light from its top. He ticked the button on the hilt, and the light sprung into life.\n\n"Well," said Hansel, "at least we have this."\n\nGretel smiled. "Good find."\n\nHansel shifted in place. The children watched on in bewilderment as the crow landed on the front windowsill of a small, cobblestone house. The crow hopped to and fro, shuffling it's feathers.
